        "## 2. Data Loading & Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)\n",
        "\n",
        "### 2.1 Loading the Data\n",
        "\n",
        "The dataset `oil_prices_2426.csv` contains **500 daily observations** of crude oil prices in US dollars, spanning from **21 September 2024** to **02 February 2026**. This covers approximately 16 months of real market data.\n",
        "\n",
        "We perform the following preprocessing steps:\n",
        "- Parse the `date` column from its `DD/MM/YYYY` string format into proper Python `datetime` objects — this is essential for time series indexing\n",
        "- Set the date as the DataFrame index so that all statsmodels functions can work with it correctly\n",
        "- Rename the price column to `price` for convenience\n",
        "- Sort by date (ascending) to ensure chronological order\n",
        "\n",
        "### 2.2 Why EDA Matters\n",
        "\n",
        "Exploratory Data Analysis is not a formality — it is a critical first step. For time series data, EDA tells us:\n",
        "- Whether the series has a **trend** (systematic increase or decrease over time)\n",
        "- Whether the series has **seasonality** (repeating cycles)\n",
        "- Whether the **variance is stable** or changes over time (heteroscedasticity)\n",
        "- Whether there are **outliers or anomalies** that could distort our model\n",
        "- The general **stationarity profile** of the series — crucial before fitting ARIMA\n",
        "\n",
        "These observations directly inform our modelling decisions."
      ]
