        "## 3. Stationarity Analysis\n",
        "\n",
        "### Why Stationarity Matters for ARIMA\n",
        "\n",
        "ARIMA (AutoRegressive Integrated Moving Average) is built upon the assumption that the time series is **weakly stationary** — meaning its statistical properties (mean, variance, autocovariance) do not change over time. If we fit an ARIMA model to a non-stationary series, the estimated coefficients will be spurious, confidence intervals unreliable, and forecasts meaningless.\n",
        "\n",
        "A series is said to contain a **unit root** if it has a stochastic trend (random walk behaviour). In such cases, first differencing `Δyₜ = yₜ − yₜ₋₁` typically removes the trend and makes the series stationary. The number of times we need to difference is the **integration order `d`** in ARIMA(p, d, q).\n",
        "\n",
        "We use three complementary approaches to test stationarity:\n",
        "\n",
        "### 3.1 Augmented Dickey-Fuller (ADF) Test\n",
        "- **Null Hypothesis H₀**: The series has a unit root (is non-stationary)\n",
        "- **Alternative H₁**: The series is stationary\n",
        "- We reject H₀ (conclude stationarity) if the **p-value < 0.05** and the ADF statistic is more negative than the critical values\n",
        "\n",
        "### 3.2 KPSS Test (Kwiatkowski–Phillips–Schmidt–Shin)\n",
        "- **Null Hypothesis H₀**: The series is stationary (trend-stationary)\n",
        "- **Alternative H₁**: The series has a unit root\n",
        "- This is the **opposite** of ADF — using both tests together gives a more robust conclusion\n",
        "- We reject H₀ (conclude non-stationarity) if **p-value < 0.05**\n",
        "\n",
        "### 3.3 ACF and PACF Plots\n",
        "- The **Autocorrelation Function (ACF)** measures the correlation between the series and its own lagged values. A slowly decaying ACF that remains significantly above zero for many lags is a visual hallmark of a non-stationary series with a unit root.\n",
        "- The **Partial Autocorrelation Function (PACF)** measures the direct correlation at each lag after removing indirect effects. Together, ACF and PACF guide us in choosing the orders `p` and `q` for the ARIMA model."
      ]
    },
