        "## 4. Making the Series Stationary via Differencing\n",
        "\n",
        "### 4.1 The Concept of Differencing\n",
        "\n",
        "Since both the ADF and KPSS tests confirm that the original series is **non-stationary** (contains a unit root), we apply **first-order differencing** to remove the trend:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\\Delta y_t = y_t - y_{t-1}$$\n",
        "\n",
        "This operation computes the **day-to-day change** in oil prices. If the original series was a random walk `yₜ = yₜ₋₁ + εₜ`, then `Δyₜ = εₜ` — pure white noise, which is stationary.\n",
        "\n",
        "### 4.2 Why Not Second-Order Differencing?\n",
        "\n",
        "We first check whether a single round of differencing is sufficient. Over-differencing (applying d=2 when d=1 suffices) introduces artificial autocorrelation and can make the model worse. We confirm the appropriate order by re-running our stationarity tests on `Δyₜ`.\n",
        "\n",
        "### 4.3 Setting the `d` parameter\n",
        "\n",
        "The result of this section directly informs the `d` parameter in our ARIMA(p, d, q) grid search. If one round of differencing achieves stationarity, `d = 1` should be the primary candidate in our search space."
      ]
