        "## 7. ARIMA — Model Evaluation & 24-Month Forecast\n",
        "\n",
        "### 7.1 Out-of-Sample Evaluation\n",
        "\n",
        "Before we forecast into the future, we must assess whether our ARIMA model can make accurate out-of-sample predictions — i.e., whether it generalises to data it has never seen. We evaluate using the **test set** (the 20% held out in Section 6).\n",
        "\n",
        "We use two complementary metrics:\n",
        "\n",
        "- **RMSE (Root Mean Squared Error)**: $\\text{RMSE} = \\sqrt{\\frac{1}{n}\\sum_{t=1}^{n}(y_t - \\hat{y}_t)^2}$ — penalises large errors more heavily due to squaring. Expressed in the same units as the target (USD).\n",
        "\n",
        "- **MAE (Mean Absolute Error)**: $\\text{MAE} = \\frac{1}{n}\\sum_{t=1}^{n}|y_t - \\hat{y}_t|$ — measures the average magnitude of errors without directional bias. More robust to outliers than RMSE.\n",
        "\n",
        "- **MAPE (Mean Absolute Percentage Error)**: $\\text{MAPE} = \\frac{100}{n}\\sum\\frac{|y_t - \\hat{y}_t|}{y_t}$ — expresses error as a percentage of actual values, enabling comparison across different price scales.\n",
        "\n",
        "### 7.2 24-Month Forecast\n",
        "\n",
        "For the final forecast, we refit the ARIMA model on the **complete dataset** (train + test) to use all available information before projecting 730 days (~24 months) into the future. The forecast includes **95% confidence intervals**, which naturally widen over the forecast horizon as uncertainty compounds."
      ]
