        "## 11. Conclusions & Future Work\n",
        "\n",
        "### Summary of Findings\n",
        "\n",
        "In this notebook, we conducted a complete time series analysis of crude oil prices\n",
        "from September 2024 to February 2026, applying two complementary forecasting\n",
        "frameworks and critically evaluating their performance.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Data & EDA:** The series exhibited a strong upward trend (rising approximately\n",
        "4× from ~$32 in September 2024 to a peak of ~$158 in late 2025), followed by a\n",
        "notable decline to ~$119 by February 2026. This confirmed strong non-stationarity.\n",
        "The 500 daily observations contained no missing values. The positive skewness and\n",
        "non-constant rolling variance further indicated that raw prices were unsuitable for\n",
        "direct ARIMA modelling without transformation.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Stationarity Analysis:** Both the Augmented Dickey-Fuller test (failure to reject\n",
        "the unit root null hypothesis, p > 0.05) and the KPSS test (rejection of the\n",
        "stationarity null, p < 0.05) independently confirmed non-stationarity in the\n",
        "original series. The ACF plot exhibited the classic slowly-decaying pattern\n",
        "characteristic of a random walk process. A single round of first-order differencing\n",
        "was sufficient to achieve stationarity confirmed by both tests on Δyₜ, establishing\n",
        "d=1 as the integration order.\n",
        "\n",
        "**ARIMA Modelling:** An exhaustive grid search over all 243 combinations of\n",
        "p ∈ [0,8], d ∈ [0,2], q ∈ [0,8] identified the optimal model via AIC. The selected\n",
        "ARIMA(p,d,q) produced a near-flat 24-month forecast of approximately ~$125–130,\n",
        "consistent with the model's last-known price anchoring behaviour under d=1\n",
        "differencing. Residual diagnostics confirmed white noise residuals with no\n",
        "significant autocorrelation remaining (Ljung-Box p > 0.05), though mild\n",
        "heteroscedasticity was observed — characteristic of commodity price volatility\n",
        "clustering.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Prophet Modelling:** Facebook Prophet with the optimal changepoint_prior_scale\n",
        "of 0.05 (selected via time-series cross-validation, achieving RMSE=25.62) provided\n",
        "a flexible, decomposable alternative. Prophet detected key trend inflection points\n",
        "and revealed interpretable seasonality components: mid-week price peaks in the\n",
        "weekly component and a November–January price elevation in the yearly component,\n",
        "consistent with seasonal energy demand patterns. However, Prophet's 24-month\n",
        "forecast of ~$256 represents an unrealistic extrapolation of the dominant upward\n",
        "trend, as the recent price decline (January–February 2026) was too short to\n",
        "override the longer trend signal. This highlights a fundamental limitation of\n",
        "both models when trained on short, non-stationary windows.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Model Comparison:** On the held-out test set (final 20% of observations),\n",
        "Prophet achieved a lower RMSE and MAPE than ARIMA, suggesting better short-term\n",
        "generalisation. However, ARIMA produced a more conservative and arguably more\n",
        "realistic 24-month forecast given the recent price decline. Neither model\n",
        "incorporates exogenous variables, which is the primary limitation for both\n",
        "approaches in this commodity forecasting context.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Comparison with Post-Forecast Reality:** The forecast horizon extends from\n",
        "February 2026 to February 2028. Real oil price data collected after the modelling\n",
        "cutoff (post-February 2026) would provide the definitive out-of-sample test.\n",
        "Based on the observed downward trend at the series end, ARIMA's conservative\n",
        "flat forecast appears more consistent with a mean-reversion scenario, while\n",
        "Prophet's upward trajectory would require a sustained supply-side shock to\n",
        "materialise. Monitoring actual prices against both forecast corridors over the\n",
        "coming months will be the ultimate validation of these models.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "### Future Improvements\n",
        "\n",
        "1. **GARCH Models:** The heteroscedasticity observed in the ARIMA residuals\n",
        "   suggests that a **GARCH(1,1)** or **EGARCH** extension would more accurately\n",
        "   model volatility clustering — a well-documented feature of energy commodity\n",
        "   prices (Engle, 1982). A GARCH layer on the ARIMA residuals would also yield\n",
        "   better-calibrated prediction intervals.\n",
        "\n",
        "2. **SARIMAX with Exogenous Variables:** Incorporating external predictors —\n",
        "   such as OPEC production volumes, the US Dollar Index (DXY), and geopolitical\n",
        "   risk indices — as exogenous regressors in a SARIMAX framework would address\n",
        "   the primary limitation identified here: both models treat oil price as a\n",
        "   purely endogenous process, ignoring the supply-demand fundamentals that\n",
        "   actually drive price dynamics.\n",
        "\n",
        "3. **LSTM Neural Networks:** A **Long Short-Term Memory (LSTM)** network\n",
        "   (Hochreiter & Schmidhuber, 1997) could capture long-range non-linear\n",
        "   dependencies that both ARIMA and Prophet's additive linear models miss —\n",
        "   particularly relevant for the regime-switching behaviour observed in\n",
        "   commodity markets.\n",
        "\n",
        "4. **Ensemble Forecasting:** Combining ARIMA and Prophet predictions via\n",
        "   weighted averaging or stacked generalisation could reduce forecast variance\n",
        "   and improve robustness, as neither model dominates across all evaluation\n",
        "   metrics (Cerqueira et al., 2020).\n",
        "\n",
        "5. **Extended Historical Data:** The current dataset spans only ~16 months.\n",
        "   Extending to 10+ years would provide richer seasonality estimation,\n",
        "   stronger stationarity test power, and more representative train/test splits —\n",
        "   particularly important for Prophet's yearly seasonality component, which was\n",
        "   estimated from less than two full annual cycles.\n",
